\title{Integration is linear map}
\taxon{Definition}
\p{
    Let #{V} be the vector space of all continuous functions on the interval #{[a,b]}.
    The map #{I: V \to V} defined by
    ##{
        I(f) = \int_a^x f(t) dt
    }
    is a \strong{linear map}.
    In other words, #{I} preserves the operations of addition and scalar multiplication:
    For all #{f,g \in V} and all #{\alpha \in \mathbb{R}},
    ##{
        I(f+g) = I(f) + I(g) \quad \text{and} \quad I(\alpha f) = \alpha I(f)
    }
}